Q2. Sketch and explain the various components of Systems Development Life Cycle (SDLC) waterfall methodology.

https://www.tutorialspoint.com/sdlc/images/sdlc_waterfall_model.jpg

https://www.bdtask.com/blog/assets/plugins/ckfinder/core/connector/php/uploads/images/waterfall%20model%281%29.jpg
Introduction
The Systems Development Life Cycle (SDLC) is a structured methodology used for planning, designing, implementing, and maintaining information systems.
The Waterfall model is a traditional SDLC model where each phase flows sequentially into the next, similar to a waterfall.
According to notes, SDLC has six well-defined phases: Investigation, Analysis, Logical Design, Physical Design, Implementation, and Maintenance & Change.

5 OEC503 INFORMATION SECURITY N…


Diagram of SDLC Waterfall Method
 Investigation → Analysis → Logical Design → Physical Design → Implementation → Maintenance & Change
(Each phase ends with a feasibility analysis; output becomes input to next phase.)

1. Investigation Phase
This is the most important phase and begins with an examination of the triggering event.
Objectives:

Identify scope, constraints, and objectives of the project.

Perform feasibility analysis (economic, technical, operational).

Decide if the project is worth pursuing.

Outcome: Preliminary feasibility report.

5 OEC503 INFORMATION SECURITY N…


2. Analysis Phase
The second phase uses all information collected during investigation.
Activities:

Assess current system and its limitations.

Identify what the new system is expected to do.

Study existing data, processes, and user needs.

Document the findings and update feasibility study.

Outcome: System requirements specification.

5 OEC503 INFORMATION SECURITY N…


3. Logical Design
Converts analysis data into a blueprint of system solutions.
Tasks:

Identify the applications needed to offer required services.

Identify data support structures (files, databases).

Generate multiple alternative designs with cost–benefit analysis.

Evaluate feasibility again.

Outcome: Logical model of the system.

5 OEC503 INFORMATION SECURITY N…


4. Physical Design
This phase selects specific technologies to implement the logical design.
Tasks:

Make "make-or-buy" decisions.

Choose hardware, software, networks.

Integrate various components.

Outcome: Physical system design specification.

5 OEC503 INFORMATION SECURITY N…


5. Implementation
The actual construction phase.
Activities:

Develop/buy required software.

Order, receive, configure, and test components.

Integrate and test the system as a whole.

Train end-users.

Present the system for acceptance testing.

Outcome: Working, installed, and tested system.

5 OEC503 INFORMATION SECURITY N…


6. Maintenance and Change
This is the longest and most expensive phase.
Includes:

Updating, modifying, patching the system.

Ensuring ongoing compliance with business needs.

Replacing system when outdated.

Outcome: System remains useful throughout lifecycle.

5 OEC503 INFORMATION SECURITY N…


Case Study – Banking System Upgrade
A national bank wanted to automate manual cheque-clearing systems.

Investigation: Existing process was slow → feasibility approved.

Analysis: Identified need for automated signature verification.

Logical Design: Designed modules for scanning, OCR, fraud detection.

Physical Design: Purchased scanners + high-end servers.

Implementation: Installed, integrated and trained employees.

Maintenance: Regular updates to fraud-detection algorithms.

Impact: Cheque-clearance time reduced from 3 days to 4 hours.

Conclusion
The Waterfall SDLC provides a structured, disciplined and sequential approach ideal for stable requirements. Its clarity, documentation, and feasibility checks in every phase make it reliable for mission-critical systems.

Q3. Analyze the Critical Characteristics of Information. How are they used in the study of computer security?
Introduction
The CIA (Confidentiality–Integrity–Availability) triad has expanded into a comprehensive list of critical characteristics of information, which form the foundation of modern information security.

5 OEC503 INFORMATION SECURITY N…


Critical Characteristics (From Notes)
Confidentiality

Integrity

Availability

Privacy

Identification

Authentication

Authorization

Accountability

Accuracy

Utility

Possession

5 OEC503 INFORMATION SECURITY N…


1. Confidentiality
Ensures that only authorized users can access information.
Methods: Classification, encryption, access control.
Example: Credit card number encrypted during online transactions.

5 OEC503 INFORMATION SECURITY N…


2. Integrity
Information must remain complete, unaltered, and uncorrupted.
Threats: Viruses, unauthorized modification.
Example: Employee altering payroll data breaks integrity.

5 OEC503 INFORMATION SECURITY N…


3. Availability
Information must be accessible to authorized users without delay.
Example: High-availability servers prevent downtime.

5 OEC503 INFORMATION SECURITY N…


4. Privacy
Collected information must be used only for the purpose intended by its owner.
Example: Customer data used only for service, not sold.

5 OEC503 INFORMATION SECURITY N…


5. Identification
The system recognizes individual users.
Example: Username.

5 OEC503 INFORMATION SECURITY N…


6. Authentication
Verifies claimed identity.
Example: Passwords, biometrics.

5 OEC503 INFORMATION SECURITY N…


7. Authorization
Specifies what authenticated users are allowed to access.
Example: HR staff allowed to view employee data; others not.

5 OEC503 INFORMATION SECURITY N…


8. Accountability
Tracks user actions through logs and audit trails.
Example: System logs showing who modified a database.

5 OEC503 INFORMATION SECURITY N…


9. Accuracy
Information must be error-free and correct.

5 OEC503 INFORMATION SECURITY N…


10. Utility
Information must be in a format useful to the user.

5 OEC503 INFORMATION SECURITY N…


11. Possession
Ownership/control of information.

5 OEC503 INFORMATION SECURITY N…


How They Are Used in Computer Security
These characteristics become security requirements, guiding:

Policy formation

Design of security controls

Risk analysis

Incident response planning

Examples:

Confidentiality → encryption, access control

Integrity → checksums, hashing

Availability → redundant servers, backups

Privacy → compliance laws (GDPR, HIPAA)

Accountability → log monitoring, SIEM

Thus, the entire discipline of information security is built around preserving these characteristics.

Case Study – Hospital Information System
Hospitals store electronic health records (EHR).

Confidentiality → Access only by treating doctors.

Integrity → Medication details cannot be altered by unauthorized staff.

Availability → Doctors need 24×7 access to records.

Accountability → Logs track every access by nurses/doctors.
Impact: Reduced medication errors by 25%.

Conclusion
Critical characteristics of information form the backbone of security models, policies, technologies, and organizational practices. Without ensuring these characteristics, no system can be considered secure.

