3. Explain in detail about NIST Security Models. (15 Marks)
Introduction
The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) provides comprehensive guidelines for security programs. These models are widely used in government and private sectors for designing, implementing, and auditing information security.

5 OEC503 INFORMATION SECURITY N…


NIST Security Models
I. NIST Risk Management Framework (RMF)
Provides a structured 6-step approach:

Categorize information systems

Select security controls

Implement security controls

Assess security controls

Authorize information system operation

Monitor controls continuously

This lifecycle ensures ongoing risk-based security.

II. NIST Special Publication 800-12
Titled “An Introduction to Computer Security: The NIST Handbook”.
It explains the security principles required for building secure systems:

Confidentiality

Integrity

Availability

Accountability

Assurance

5 OEC503 INFORMATION SECURITY N…


III. NIST SP 800-14 – Security Principles
Lists 8 security principles & 14 practices, including:

Security must support mission

Security is cost-effective

Security decisions must be based on risk

Security must be integrated into system lifecycle

Require accountability & proper authorization
This shaped modern security architectures.

IV. NIST SP 800-18 – Security Planning Guide
Assists in creating:

System security plans

Roles & responsibilities

Minimum baseline controls
Used for government accreditation.

V. NIST SP 800-30 – Risk Management Guide
A full risk assessment model stating:

Threat identification

Vulnerability identification

Likelihood calculation

Impact analysis

Risk determination

Recommended controls

5 OEC503 INFORMATION SECURITY N…


This is also the source of risk calculation used in your notes.

VI. NIST SP 800-53 – Security Controls Catalog
Defines 18 security control families, such as:

AC (Access Control)

AT (Awareness & Training)

AU (Audit & Accountability)

SC (System & Communications Protection)

IR (Incident Response)
Used widely for federal security compliance.

VII. NIST Cybersecurity Framework (CSF)
Organizes cybersecurity into 5 major functions:

Identify

Protect

Detect

Respond

Recover

This is the modern gold-standard framework.

Conclusion
NIST security models provide comprehensive guidelines from risk management to security planning, control implementation, monitoring, and continuous improvement. They form the backbone of modern cybersecurity programs.

4. Demonstrate with a diagram the guidelines and purposes of ISO/IEC 17799. (15 Marks)
Introduction
ISO/IEC 17799 (now ISO/IEC 27002) is an international standard providing best practices for information security management.
It outlines controls to protect confidentiality, integrity, and availability of information.

