1. Analyze the concept of cryptography and its importance in securing communications. Compare symmetric and asymmetric encryption techniques with real-world examples. (15 Marks)
Introduction
Cryptography is the science of protecting information by transforming it into an unreadable form so that only authorized users can access it.
It ensures four fundamental security services:

Confidentiality – keeping data secret

Integrity – preventing unauthorized modification

Authentication – verifying identities

Non-repudiation – preventing denial of actions

5 OEC503 INFORMATION SECURITY N…


Cryptography is crucial in modern communication systems such as banking, e-commerce, email, cloud storage, VPNs, and military communication.

Concept of Cryptography
Cryptography uses mathematical algorithms and keys to convert plaintext (readable data) into ciphertext (unreadable data).

Basic operations:
Encryption – Plaintext → Ciphertext

Decryption – Ciphertext → Plaintext

Key – Secret value used in encryption/decryption

Cipher – The algorithm (AES, DES, RSA, etc.)

Types of cryptography
Symmetric key cryptography

Asymmetric key cryptography

Hash functions

Importance of Cryptography in Securing Communications
1. Protects Data Confidentiality
Only authorized entities can read the message.
Example: Secure messaging apps (WhatsApp, Signal) use encryption.

2. Ensures Data Integrity
Cryptographic hash functions ensure data has not been changed during transmission.

3. Provides Authentication
Digital signatures and certificates verify identity.

4. Enables Secure E-Commerce
Online banking, UPI transactions, and credit card payments use TLS/SSL encryption.

5. Prevents Eavesdropping & Man-in-the-Middle Attacks
Attackers cannot read or modify encrypted traffic.

6. Essential for National Security
Governments and military rely on cryptography to protect classified data.

Comparison: Symmetric vs. Asymmetric Encryption
Feature	Symmetric Encryption	Asymmetric Encryption
Keys Used	Single key (same for encryption & decryption)	Two keys – Public key (encrypt), Private key (decrypt)
Speed	Fast & efficient	Slow due to complex maths
Key Distribution	Problematic (must share key secretly)	Secure key sharing (public key can be openly distributed)
Best Use Case	Encrypting large data volumes	Securely exchanging keys, digital signatures
Algorithms	AES, DES, 3DES, Blowfish	RSA, ECC, Diffie-Hellman
Security Level	Strong but depends on key secrecy	Very strong due to mathematical hardness (factorization/elliptic curves)
Real-World Use Cases
Symmetric Encryption (Examples)
1. AES encryption in Wi-Fi security
WPA2/WPA3 use AES for fast bulk encryption of wireless communication.

2. Disk Encryption
BitLocker and FileVault use AES to encrypt entire hard drives.

3. Payment Systems
Credit card data is encrypted using symmetric keys before transmission.

Asymmetric Encryption (Examples)
1. SSL/TLS Handshake
Websites use:

Browser encrypts data with server’s public key (RSA/ECC)

Server decrypts using private key
Used in HTTPS (e.g., banks, Amazon, Gmail).

2. Digital Signatures
Used in Aadhaar authentication, PAN systems, e-filing.
Ensures integrity + origin authenticity.

3. Cryptocurrencies
Bitcoin and Ethereum use public key cryptography (ECC) to verify ownership of coins.

How Symmetric and Asymmetric Work Together (Hybrid Encryption)
Modern systems use both:

Asymmetric (RSA/ECC) → To securely exchange a symmetric AES session key

Symmetric (AES) → To encrypt the actual data

Used in:

SSL/TLS

WhatsApp end-to-end encryption

Cloud storage services

Conclusion
Cryptography is the backbone of secure communication.
Symmetric encryption is fast for bulk data, while asymmetric encryption solves the key distribution problem. Modern systems combine both to achieve optimal security and performance.

