5. Safeguarding Storage Media
Locked storage

Secure backups

Off-site DR backup storage

Controlled disposal through shredding

6. Controls for Human Entry
Visitor logs

Escorting visitors

Access badges

Security awareness programs

7. Physical Barriers
Fences

Gates

Turnstiles

Security doors

Bulletproof glass

III. Threats Prevented by Physical Security
From your notes, physical security protects against:

Theft

Vandalism

Espionage

Natural disasters

Sabotage

Unauthorized access

5 OEC503 INFORMATION SECURITY N…


IV. Case Study – Data Center Example
A financial institution experienced unauthorized entry by a contractor.
Implementation of physical controls prevented attacks:

Biometric scanners

Mantrap entry

CCTV

Guard patrol

Result: No further unauthorized access; compliance with regulatory audits improved.

Conclusion
Physical security is the first and most critical line of defense in information security. It protects people, facilities, and equipment from environmental, accidental, and intentional threats. Without it, even the strongest cyber defenses can be easily bypassed.

